    <p>
      Most free online image tools follow the same business model: you upload your files to their server, and they process them in exchange for the right to collect your data. That data might be used to train AI models, serve targeted ads, or build a profile of your activity. The privacy policy usually permits all of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Browser-based image tools offer an alternative. The entire application — decoding, encoding, resizing — runs in JavaScript and WebAssembly inside your browser tab. Your files never travel over the network. No server sees your photos. No database stores your uploads. Here is why that matters.
    </p>
    <h2>The server upload problem</h2>
    <p>
      When you upload an image to a server, you lose control over it. The server operator can:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Store a copy indefinitely, even if they promise to delete it</li>
      <li>Analyse the image with AI to extract metadata, objects, faces, or text</li>
      <li>Use the image to train machine learning models</li>
      <li>Share or sell the data to third parties</li>
      <li>Lose the data in a breach</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Privacy policies often grant these rights explicitly. Even services with good intentions are vulnerable to data breaches and government requests. A server-side tool that promises privacy is still a server with your files on it.
    </p>
    <h2>How browser-based processing works</h2>
    <p>
      A browser-based tool loads the entire application code into your browser when you visit the page. When you drop an image onto the upload zone, the file is read into memory using the File API. The processing — compression, resizing, format conversion — happens using WebAssembly codecs compiled from C libraries. The result is written back to a download link using the URL.createObjectURL API.
    </p>
    <p>
      At no point does the file travel over the network. The only network requests are for the initial page load. There is no server endpoint to upload to, no API to call, no database to store metadata.
    </p>
    <h2>What this means for your privacy</h2>
    <p>
      Browser-based processing eliminates the most common privacy risks associated with online image tools. If there is no server receiving your files, there is no server that can be breached, subpoenaed, or monetised. Your images exist only in your device's memory, and they disappear when you close the tab.
